                    "company": "Eindhoven University of Technology",
                    "description": "My Ph.D. research focuses on theoretical models for the spread of information and diseases in models for real-world networks. I was expecting to only publish research in high-quality theoretical journals (two papers published, two more submitted papers, all as main author). However, the COVID outbreak  led to an applied research line, with two simulation-based papers in well-known journals discussing the effects of temporary immunity and usage of contact-tracing applications. In these two projects I was the responsible person for defining research questions, setting up the experiments, and writing tested software. As side projects I have collaborated on two papers that explain how/why certain machine learning algorithms/models work, one of which was awarded with a Runner-up award at a conference.\n\nBesides doing research, I have supervised a master's student, and I have been an instructor for several courses: I have been awarded a Certificate of Excellence as an instructor for Statistical Learning Theory. I was also one of the initiators and main organisers of a 9-day workshop for 85 researchers (audience ranging from Ph.D. students to the top professors in the field). Besides running the day-to-day organization, I was responsible (together with my co-organiser) for gathering funding, inviting speakers, and communicating with attendees from all over the world.\n\nI have visited ETH Zurich and Pontificia Universidad de Chile for multiple months/weeks.",
